segments.text: Thomas F. Urban of Senator Ralph W. Yarborough on April 22, 1985.
In 1964, President Lyndon Johnson stated, quote, I don't think Texas has had a senator that voted for the people more than Senator Yarborough has voted for them.
And no member of the U.S. Senate has stood up and fought for me or fought for the people more since I became president than Ralph Yarborough.
What was your relationship with President Johnson, and how did it change over the years as he was first senior senator from Texas and later vice president and president?
Well, when I first went to the Senate, of course, Johnson had opposed my election.
He had opposed it from the governor and then all the way through.
His was the big money of Texas, and I represented the people.
Now, Johnson was a very, very clever politician.
He would vote for the people on a number of issues, but
enough to say he was progressive, but not to alienate that vast big money that was supporting him.
And some average senator, like the two we've got now, one Bo Weaver and one Republican, they just voted against the people the majority of the time, the whole time.
Johnson didn't.
If it was a matter affecting union labor, he generally voted with the big contracts.
If it was a matter that affected the poor, he would vote with Sam Rayburn for Social Security and things like that.
So, he didn't want to see anybody else coming along with the record that I had of voting for people all the time.
Because he told friends he wanted to be president, and all of Newark around Washington told him that he voted the way he voted against the blacks.
He could never be president.
He told them that...
He had to get elected.
He couldn't be president if he wasn't elected first, and then the Senate.
He had to vote that way in Texas.
They'd have to understand if you didn't vote that way, you couldn't be elected.

Well, when I voted on, when I was elected with no money, you might say, on the platform of fairness and equal treatment to everybody, Johnson immediately switched and began to support civil rights bills, and all of them had been introduced.
That was a big switch in his...
He didn't switch his...
his position.
He had opposed me in those races, so when he ran for the Presidency in 1960, I supported John F. Kennedy.
Johnston was very mad about that.
I wasn't particularly sore with him.
I felt better about my relationship with him.
I repaid him.
I showed him he couldn't bluff me.
I wasn't afraid of him, so I just wanted to let him know I was his
that I was his equal in independence of thought.
Couldn't push me around.
He thought that being vice president, later president, people from Texas ought to take orders from him.
Thought I would take orders from him.
I supported my own bills, whether he was for or against them.
But our relationship was not a bitter relationship that's been painted up in the press a lot.
He appointed my son member of the Indian Claims Commission, where he served 11 years, and I very much appreciate that.
I have at least 30 autographed photographs of Lyndon Johnson and me over the years.
I was down at the White House a lot.
He told me one time, he said, Ralph, you never give me any property.
Come down here and talk.
And you don't go down back and make a statement about it.
I never did make a statement about it, as it does the White House.
I knew he had the power the next day to say, well, that isn't so.
That's not what I said.
And I wasn't going to give him that chance.
But what he had me down there for was a judiciary appointment of judges in Texas.
It was my patronage that he was trying to trade me out of.
Johnson was a real horse trader, the best I've ever seen.
He was cunning as a fox and a coyote combined.
He was a real 100% politician.
That's what made him effective in legislation.
To him, the politics of it was all up to what he could do and how the people would respond.
How did your role as a major carrier of legislation change between administrations of Presidents Kennedy and then later President Johnson?
There's a constant evolution in that role.
When I first got there with Johnson, the majority leader of the Senate, it was very difficult to get anything passed.
I got very little passed as long as he was the majority leader of the Senate because he was blocking all of it.
He had put the chairman in their positions.
I was a co-author of a good many important bills.
I had a role in it because if I introduced the bill by myself or put my name first on it,
I'd get a lot of other people to put their names and then put mine where really in the background I was pushing it harder than anybody.
And I got legislation passed that way but I didn't issue any statement to the press as my legislation because I didn't want to get snarled in the House.
Now Lyndon could not block all legislation in the Senate.
even if he didn't want it.
I mean, even while he was majority leader directly, but he could indirectly due to his great influence with Sam Rayburn.
Sam Rayburn had the house right in the palm of his hands.
He was a terrific speaker, dynamic in his organizational skills, and very modest about it all the time.
Didn't claim that power, but he had it, and he was such a believer in Lyndon Johnson.
If Lyndon came over and told him a senator hadn't treated him fairly, he'd bottle that senator's bills up and never let any pass.
So you had to think of Sam Rayburn.
And so I'm co-author of a number of beneficial bills during the years that Lyndon was majority leader, but that my name first, my bills, no, I couldn't get them back up.
One passed, the Cold War GI Bill.
Lyndon and John F. Kennedy both helped me on that.
Taylor Strong, Eisenhower's president,
He was opposed to the Cold War GI Bill, and they were each running for the presidency, and they got right in behind him.
Well, we passed it in the Senate, and Eisenhower was able to block it in the House.
Tiger Teeth blocked it for him because the president asked him to in the House.
And when Kennedy came in as the president, I went down to see him about it.
He'd been on that committee and helped us pass it that time.
I was telling you about it when we passed it in 57, I believe, to 31 over the Republicans in Eisenhower's opposition.
Kennedy's answer says, yes, Ralph, but I'm president now.
And then when Johnson became president, I went back again to try to pass it.
I passed it two or three times.
It took eight years to get it finally written into law.
And Lyndon must have been reading John F. Kennedy's tapes.
He always had those tapes.
Because he looked at me and smiled and said, yes, Ralph, but I'm president now.
When I told him he'd help me pass it.
That's what took me eight years.
The hardest, longest fight I had was to pass that.
Cold War GI Bill, but I've got the tremendous satisfaction, it is to me tremendous, of seeing that eight million veterans at least have gotten an education on that bill.
In what ways did your views on civil rights legislation vary from President Johnson's?
Practically none.
Okay.
Practically none, we're both supportive.
I don't think Johnson had before I got there.
But when I got there, he turned around 180 degrees.
He became stronger than he was before.
The difference between us was he was in the leadership role, and I had very little seniority.
I wasn't on the Judiciary Committee.
I wasn't on the committee to handle the bills.
So my role was merely a supportive role to support him.
But where I was having the most influence in

was on the committees i was on i was on the educational subcommittee went on it in january of 1958 stayed there 13 years and was author a co-author of every major educational bill in that time and i was having there because that committee was split one time another dirksen strom thurman and uh goldwater all of them in there to fight us on another bill and i was only fighting for those
education built because I taught school three years in the rural schools of Henderson County.
I taught briefly in the University of Texas Law School.
I served four years as the counsel for the Texas State Teachers Association, one there.
I had been on the Texas State Board of Law Examiners four years.
I represented a bunch of school districts and colleges in their litigation.

And during the big years that I served education, while I was assistant attorney general under Jimmy Allred, where this plaque the land office gave me in January 31st of this year, they have since audited what happened to the judgments I won in the oil lands of Texas.
I had the land desk at four years under Allred.

And the opinions I wrote that are still being followed in the land office, and they've given me this plaque that says that I enriched the permanent school fund by more than two-tenths of a billion dollars.
And the whole size of it is four-tenths of a billion.
Now that's half of it.
That was the greatest educational contribution I've made in my life.
And it's because I started off as a rural school teacher when I was 17.
and the one teacher of rural school.
My youngest pupil was six and my oldest was 25 and we had a ball.
In 1969, you became chairman of the powerful Labor and Public Welfare Committee, which President Johnson stated was responsible for 80% of the legislation passed by the 89th Congress.
What made this committee so prolific in the passage of legislation?
Because of its jurisdictional setup.
Each committee has jurisdiction over certain things, armed services, military bills, interior and insular affairs.
over islands and over national parks and over Indian reservations and so forth, commerce over railroads and the Federal Railway Act and aviation and civil air.
By jurisdiction, we had, Labor and Public Welfare Committee had jurisdiction over labor legislation, over all educational legislation, all health legislation.
All veterans' education and hospitalization, not the pensions, that went over under taxation.
But all hospital, veterans' hospital, all veterans' education, we had.
My GI Bill was there.
I could pass a proposal on that committee.
And a number of other things.
We had jurisdiction over the poverty bill.
We had jurisdiction over the food stamp problem at first.
And a number of bills like that.
We had jurisdiction over so many things.
And we came through that.
Those were the things I was, those were the things I'd run for governor of Texas three times on to improve the education of our low standing in the union.
In public health at that time, Texas was 46 out of the 48 states.
We're very low.
We're still low.
We're 39th, we're 49th in the union in the size of our old age picture.
And we're the richest state in the union.
We're 49th in the union in the average

payment for the dependent child i ran for governor on those a great disappointment for me in life is that they're still there 49th down this rich terribly rich state i mean terribly tremendously rich state i meant to say and we pay something like 30 some odd dollars and i think that at this time south carolina is the only state in the western mississippi those two generally are they've gone up and i helped pass
They put two more states in the union while I was there.
So that didn't improve Texas standing in it.
We fell from 46 to 48 and 49.
They went ahead of Texas in those things.
But we passed that legislation because that's the committee it came to.
And we got on that committee, a bunch like myself got on it because we were for it.
I'm going to stop there.
A number of major political leaders have served as members of this committee over the years, including John F. Kennedy, Richard M. Nixon, Hubert H. Humphrey, Robert F. Kennedy, and Barry Goldwater.
And then while you were chairman, Edward M. Kennedy, Walter F. Mondale, Alan Cranston, Jacob Javits, and Richard Schweiker.
Why do you think this committee drew such great leaders?
Because it was the committee that did things for people.
It did more things for people than practically all the rest of the committees in there combined.
And if you wanted to serve people, if you wanted to get something done for people, you gravitated to that committee.
When I went on the education subcommittee, nobody wanted on it.
And it was easy.
I got on that with Johnson's help.
He had a hard decision to make.
Senator McNeely from
West Virginia had died with cancer, and so he was on the committee.

And labor was very strong for Joe Clark, a strong, very liberal senator from Pennsylvania, a Harvard graduate and the first reformed mayor, honest mayor that Pennsylvania had had since the Civil War, noted for corruption, one of the most corrupt city governments.
He got elected on the campaign to clean up Philadelphia and went on to Senate.
He wanted to be on that committee, and the Republicans had somebody else, Goldwater or somebody.
I mean, this was the Democratic seat.
I mean, Strom Thurmond was a Democrat then.
They wanted Strom Thurmond on it.
And Johnson, Queen of Rock in a hard place.
As you go inside, there's the liberals and the conservatives.
Well, I had just reached the Senate.
It's been there a few months.
Nobody knew really what I'd do.
Now, this is Johnson.
I didn't go around advertising what I was going to put on there.
So Johnson brought up the question of putting me on it.
Now, I think he had some ulterior motives, too.
He thought being on the labor committee that I would alienate the people of Texas so it would defeat me.
But that didn't worry me.
I saw a chance to get on the committee that I most wanted on, education.
And I got on it when I did a Republican senator from Kentucky, one of my friends I had in the Senate, and knew him in the past years, John Sherman Cooper, a great senator.
He came to me and said, Ralph, what on earth are you getting on that education subcommittee for?
Don't you know it'll beat you?
When Happy Chandler left the Senate to be baseball commissioner, they put me on it.
I'd just been appointed by the governor as a vacancy.
It beat me at the next election.
Then he became ambassador to India and made a great record.
They came back, they put him on it.
When Alvin Barkley died with a heart attack, he was appointed again by the governor.
He went back on it.

it beat him again and he came back a third time then got elected to put him back on he said they put me back on third time see it's just about four months i said yeah and he said i'm getting off and did that week i said well he said why are you staying i said because i came here to try to do something about education he said that's the lowest cause and uh the uh
I said, well, I'm going to do something about it, or I'll get beat trying, one of the two, or die trying.
Well, it had been a lost cause.
The education bill had been killed for 20 years there in the Congress.
But the Russians had put up Sputnik 1 in October of 57.
People were terribly afraid.
They'd fallen behind in science, fallen behind in mathematics, engineering.
They didn't quite know which people without skills out, but they knew something was wrong for the Russians to be ahead of us.

And so there was a great push to catch up, and we passed the National Defense Educational Act that year with seven great titles, and it covers everything from the primer through the 5,500 graduate slots for people to get PhDs.
It was a great, one of the great breakthrough legislative acts in the history of American education, federal aid to education.
One of the biggest, one historian says it's a moral land grant

College Act founding the the land-grant colleges of which Texas A&M was one that founded under that act with federal land grants and they said this is great by far the greatest act since that 1862 that Lincoln signed and so that and being on that committee I had was able to pass a lot of legislation I did not
put in my main time on the elementary and secondary, that's grade and high school.
I saw by the time I went there that the average child
school child had a chance to go through a public high school free, tuition free, that blocked him when he wanted to go to college.
When I went on that committee, there were only three million students in college in America, all kinds of colleges, senior, junior, medical, everything you had above high school, just three million.
That's where I put my work.
That's where I passed the bill.
That's where I had the greatest influence.
I concentrated on that.
And many others were fighting very hard over the elementary and secondary over two things.
religion, difference of religion, parochial schools, or race.
And I put my effort in on the higher education.
It wasn't centered there.
They were fighting those other issues down in the trenches, lower down.
And I got my higher education bills through, and when I left there, we had 11 million people in college in the United States.
That's the greatest contribution that I made in the Senate, I think.
Now, of course, I couldn't do that by myself.
I didn't do all that.
And I think except for my Cold War GI Bill, most of the bills would have passed if I hadn't been there.
But there wouldn't have been as many people in college.
I was on the Appropriations Committee, too.
I got on that with six years to go.
And I had six years of my last six years as on the Appropriations Committee, 13 years on the Education Committee.
I can say truthfully without boasting, I rolled it.
I opened the doors to colleges in America so the youth of America could get inside.
How do you think civil rights advances would have been aided if either Hubert Humphrey or Robert Kennedy would have been elected president instead of Richard Nixon in 1968?
Oh, I think that they would have advanced faster, though one thing that's overlooked are the extraneous factors
A lot of influence on civil rights.
A lot of things outside the halls of Congress or the President's speeches had a great influence.
The civil rights bill that passed when Johnson was in and got so much acclaim for because he really put his shoulder to the wheel on that civil rights bill and put his mark on it.
And while I was putting mine on education, he put his on it, but it was being filibustered.
And the general thought in the Senate was if you've got 24 filibustering and you have 24 hour sessions a day, they need to stand up and keep talking.
You can't break it if the 24 wouldn't work at it.
Of course, they've got to have some additional votes.
They've got to have a three-fifth can break it.
So if you've got 24 active workers, they can probably stall the bill.
And they thought that civil rights bill was stalled.
And then the Selma riots took place.
It was shown on television all over the United States with policemen riding those marchers trying to march from Selma to Montgomery, Alabama to petition Governor Wallace.
They tried to ride them down, they rode them down with horses, turned fire, turned police dogs, and was tearing and pulling them down the street.
That so shocked the people of America.

The whole nation was so shocked by this that the pressure had plopped like that, that the whole idea that the filibusters were left standing alone, and it turned all the doubters, all the undecideds, and all those that were maybe with them but weren't telling anybody that, it turned them over for a patient.
The second one was the open housing bill, the real estate, the homes, open houses, the people of all races couldn't discriminate against it.
Now, that one was really bogged down,
because the real estate lobbyists, in fighting the civil rights bill, there was no big money back at that time.
Airlines didn't want segregation.

Trains and buses didn't want segregation in transportation because they're just too expensive and unwieldy to try to have a black and white section and have a plane, et cetera, and all those interests.
But when you got to housing,
That broke the real estate interest in the vast billions of dollars, scores of billions of dollars involved.
But it would affect the values of the homes they were selling, the value of real estate was involved in them.
The big money was on the side of blocking that bill.
And I think it's virtually blocked when Martin Luther King was assassinated in Memphis.
And when he was assassinated, it turned sentiment around just like the earlier Selma routes turned down.
turned the civil rights bill around.

And while Hubert Humphrey and Robert Kennedy would have been strong exponents of faster advance in civil rights, at the same time, without those extraneous things happening, the first civil rights bill would not have moved fast.
In time, it would have become low.
In time, the opening housing would have become low.
But it would be stalled for years.
It would take years and years.
Those events catapulted them right onto the law books.
You once had a campaign slogan, Ralph Yarborough fights the people's battles and he wins them.
Was this really an accurate count of your victories in the Senate?
And what do you see as your main victories in the Senate?
And if any, did you have any shortcomings?
Did the Senate oppose any of your major legislation?
Yes, the main victories I won were in the field of education, and I think composite on higher education.
We had to pass a higher education facility bill.
Most colleges don't use college as a generic term of university, college, junior college, and all.
Very few have the financial resources that Texas and A&M University in Texas have, dividing the permanent fund.
Very few.
Harvard and a few great ones like that, Princeton, Yale, Stanford, California, some do.
So without the money, even though we increased the college enrollment about four-fold, unless they had money to build the buildings, they couldn't have taken care of it.

So we passed the higher education facilities bill to give money to public colleges, both to direct money or lend it to a church-related school, let them build by paying interest on it, paying it back, and giving it to independent schools like Rice and Stanford, where they had no church connection.
The constitutional innovation against government financing churches, we did not have gifts to church-related schools.
And it enhanced college education greatly.
I think I made a major contribution there, I think, leaving one in the Senate on that.
Because, as I say, most of those bills, if I hadn't been there, I think would have passed in some form.
But it depends on who's out there working on them.
I've had members of the House tell me, I'd go over and talk to House members.
You're the only look up in amazement.
You're the only senator who ever darted my door.
Why, a senator from my home state wouldn't even come over here at the house side to see me.
I worked on it.
The police guards after we started bumming things in Washington had to have everything guarded.
You just go in one door.
We worked openly the first few years.
Staff would come back and work till midnight, and then it wasn't safe any longer to be attacked on the streets.
And so I lived right across the street from the Senate office building, my apartment.
And the guards told me I was the only senator in those closing years who came and worked in his office at night.
He takes work.
They work like you see that in lawsuits.
If you don't prepare, if you don't work at it, you're going to get beat.
And I worked at those laws.
I didn't interview civilians or leave.
You had to go see people.
You had to see people that hadn't decided on it and try to get them to agree with you individually.
As soon as the House members, I worked everywhere.
What do you think was the major legislation that you worked for that didn't pass?
The major one that I worked for that didn't pass?
The major one I worked for that didn't pass was the space program and the satellites up there.
The government spent $25 billion on that and financed it, and I thought they ought to remain in government ownership and to pass the bill to...
to create a corporation to turn it over to, to give them away to a corporation, a special corporation, a government created.
I fought that, filibustered on that, and I filibustered or failed.
That's the only time I filibustered a bill while I was there.
who were coming along pretty well to one of our main filibusters, jumped up and called Mansfield a liar, and it wasn't true.
He wasn't that bad.
He hadn't taken any part in it.
He was sitting there as majority leader all the time.
And just like the Jewish prayer, the thing, and made an infuriate to all the senators, and virtually one of the filibusters, virtually a boat cow filibuster, always wondered why he did it.
Do you feel that your views while you're in the Senate changed?
over time?
Well, the opportunities changed.
See, when I went there, I went there wanting on the Appropriations Committee because I lived here at Austin.
I knew where the power was and I'd served in the Army in World War II.
I'd been in West Point a year.
I had been a staff officer on the men's division for two years and 11 months.
I went in wanting on the Armed Services Committee and had all those posts over Texas.
I was a reserve lieutenant colonel then, and I wanted to own that.
Well, Johnson was on it.
You couldn't be on the same one, the same party, the same state.
You might have your different parties.
And I wanted to own the Appropriations Committee because they're the ones dividing the money.
That meant enough political power to do something and put that money.
If you own the Appropriations Committee when the pie is cut, you can get to share for your people that you vote for all these years in campaigns.
Well, Johnson was on that, too, so that was, I was barred.

And I took what I could get in the way of the steering committee of recommendation committees, and I took what I could get, but fortuitously, I got on one that I wanted very badly, labor and public welfare, because aside from the public welfare, the food for the starving, I wanted that, and the fair shake for labor, I wanted, above all, education and health.
the health condition of Texas so bad.
Now, what I did for education helped the education nation and helped health in Texas, but it didn't push Texas up ahead of other states.
It was even for the whole nation, but it meant much more.
And so that was a thing that I never dreamed I would have, and I went there.
I thought other senators, senior to me, it'd be years before I could get on it.
I was very much interested in parks, but the Interior and Insular Committee
Generally went to Western Center because they had the Indian reservations, the national parks, everything there.
I had a very good fortune there of passing more national park legislation than anyone else, I think, in the Senate while I was there.
I wasn't on the committee, but Senator Scoop Jackson, the chairman of the school committee, was a good friend of mine.
His wife, he was down here during World War II, met a young lady from Georgetown, married her.
His wife was from Georgetown, Texas.
He'd help me in every bill.
The chairman of the parks committee, subcommittee, out in Bible, wasn't for my bills because he was Lyndon's good friend and I was the author of the bills and they were trying to block them.
Scoop Jackson made him bring my bills out of that subcommittee.
I never heard in my whole years in the Senate, I never heard any other chairman of the full committee order.
a chairman of the subcommittee under him to bring those bills out.
I was a very great friend.
But I ended up as the author of the board of the Mountain National Park, the Padre Island National Seashore Park, and the first big picket bill ever introduced.
I wasn't able to get that passed while I was there, except in the Senate the last few months.
It was too late to get it to the House.
But I kept working on it and served two terms as

chairman of the big big association in Texas and we finally the whole group of us I just wanted that but the fact that I'd been there I knew members of that committee in the house went around Republicans on the house committee told me they'd help me get my bill through this land only bill was up there lobbying on that for left and locked to stay in lobby for money and I wasn't up there lobbying for any corporations anything so they were pretty sympathetic
the Civil Rights Reform in the Senate, especially from other Southern Senators?
Well, they, I didn't have much sympathy for them when I'd come out in the Education Bill.
They were mad.
See, Johnson promoted this, well, with Dick Russell and all.
I wouldn't sign the Southern Manifesto when I went down.
And that, Johnson promoted it.
They knew he was running for President.
They'd excuse him.
See, he got himself excused.
But he did, he was trying to dynamite in other bills.
He knew what I was working on in education.
He was trying to dynamite, not necessarily against him, but he was supposed to bypass them because I hadn't supported him, wasn't supporting him, the president didn't.
And so he got to be president.
And then I was supposed to change the courses in midstream and lose my race.
And furthermore, once he got to be president, he'd sign any bill I could pass.
I was past them.
I was getting all my bills signed.
Of course, he had claimed credit when he signed them.
This is my great society.
Turned around, one of my educational bills gave me a big old smile and says, Ralph,
80% of all of my great society legislation goes through your committee.
And he had all those members of the House and Senate press turn around and smile at me, saying, I've got your stuff and I've got it and you haven't.
But the bills are low.
The main thing was to cut the bills off.
I didn't quibble with him.
I didn't get out and make speeches and say he's trying to steal my credit.
I did not stir up a quarrel with him.
I wanted the law, the main thing, what did you pass?
And the Dallas News admitted after I was defeated, of course, that I'd passed more national legislation than any other senator in the history of the Senate in Texas.
I was still there when they wrote that, so the staffers and I went over to the Library of Congress where they have the records and got their help.
You'd call them during the Senate to dig out.
They dug out, and I hadn't passed more national.
Dallas News said national.
boondoggle and get a bridge for your district, you know, or something, a new post office building.
That's a bill, but they weren't counting those.
They counted something that affected the whole nation, like education and health.
I've got some in this year of that in the materials I gave you that you'll find in what I've said, but it's substantial.
The early 1970s was a time of great scandal exposition, primarily Watergate and the Sharpstown scandals.
You've always been an outspoken fighter of corruption.
Do you think that this corruption is as pervasive in recent years as it was in the 60s and 70s?
Probably more so, but probably more subtle.
Not as brazen, not as open, not as brash.
And a lot of things that were corruption then are not now.
The common cause got this pact law passed so the corporations can contribute millions.
It's illegal then for corporations to contribute to political campaigns.
They've legalized corruption.
It's not corruption anymore, but it's legal for them to give everything they want to by the organization of pacts to candidates.
They spend as much as a half million or a million dollars
on one candidate and one congressional race over and over.
And they left them generally when they did that.
Most of those got elected.
And the influence of the vast wealth is incomprehensibly greater now than it was when I was there.
The special interests have a... And they've even turned around.
They call poor people and they call the old-age pensioners and the poor people and the hungry the special interests.
And the big papers swallow it because they're big interests too, you know.
They got that money while they sold the Dallas Times Herald years ago when it wasn't worth near as much as it is now for $97 million.
And when that interest rate went up under Carter and Reagan's 20%, they didn't agree.
That's what was causing the inflation.
The high interest rate was the most inflationary thing in our economy.
They were blaming it on labor, and they were blaming it on all kinds of things, these appropriations.
wife and I was there running when they were beating me in 70 said I busted the budget.
The total budget was only $200 billion.
It's $850 billion.
It's jumped up now $900 billion.
Reagan's busting it with this ungodly expenditures for everything that you can shoot on Earth and now going out into space dumping something to shoot at.
He's got to have a space war.
Somebody shouldn't have let him see that motion picture of Star Wars.
Who do you think is the examples of, you know, people who have been elected by PAC money, especially like in Texas?
Well, Phil Graham is one.
Bill Williams, Helms in North Carolina.
A number of those senators that you, they published figures, five, six, seven, eight million.
The PAC money, Benson spent about,

What do you think should be done to fight graft in public office, especially in Washington and Austin?
It takes education of the people.
It takes candidates that are willing to run and put their neck on the line and denounce it and expose it.
And it's a tough issue to get elected on unless you've got somebody indicted or something that you would like the public to show that people
They're not apt to believe it.
Or they see a lot of graft in their local officers and they think that's everybody in the office is crooked.
That's a, the big interest, don't mind people believing they're buying all this crooked because that excuses their account.
It takes constant education.
It's a different world.
In the world in which I grew up, I'm 81, I'm 14, the time I grew up,
accepting money from somebody, passing bills was a disgrace.
That was a man, the highest disgrace you could have was taking money under the table from the public office.
It's not people that don't favor it now, but they kind of wink at it.
And they say, well, they all do that.
With this big contribution, such a high percentage, you win, they have to take it.
But on the other hand,

Now they know in advance how they stand on these bills and raise the money and put them in.
It's legal to contribute the money with the PACs.
They know in advance how they're going to vote, so they don't pay them money after they get in the vote.

What do you think can be done to elect public officials who represent the interests of the common man rather than the special interests of big business?
Well, I think organizations to help in that are growing.
The consumer groups in Texas are growing.
They were practically unknown when I was running, very small in my last race.
The Sierra Club
has 12,000 members in Texas now on conservation issues, on environmental issues.

environmental issues, protection of wildlife, the creation of parks, was just practically non-existent.
